   <abstract >This study focuses on the Israelite House of David, an early twentieth century American communal society in Benton Harbor, Michigan. It argues that they invested in pleasure as a form of embodied religious expression through practices such as baseball. Playing baseball generated excitement and aroused intense feelings, which could be understood as either favorable or problematic. Baseball, played with properly managed pleasure, provided a means through which to assert themselves against other groups and to generate publicity. In the Israelite House of David, a Progressive Era emphasis on masculine virility merged with a renewed commitment to a Victorian era emphasis on internal piety. As American society moved from a culture of character to a culture of personality, and from an economy centered on production to one focused on consumption, the Israelite House of David fully embraced the moment. By including the Israelite House of David and their baseball teams in the story of American religion, sports, and citizenship, a new picture emerges that brings into focus the deliberative fundamentalist opposition to popular modes of "muscular Christianity" and the conscious revolt against assimilation goals. It also reveals the exhaustive efforts that such groups undertook to construct their ideal society and implement their own social reforms.</abstract>
